{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_14","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"python ./scripts/discussion_query.py spaceship-titanic --search NaNs --limit 10 --as-json\npython ./scripts/discussion_query.py spaceship-titanic --search \\\"Feature engineering\\\" --limit 10 --as-json\npython ./scripts/discussion_query.py spaceship-titanic --search Cabin --limit 10 --as-json\nprintf '\\\\n--- kernel signals ---\\\\n'\nrg -n \\\"score|Accuracy|public|CatBoost|XGB|LightGBM|RandomForest|TFDF|Gradient|ExtraTrees|ensemble|Voting|Stack|pseudo|CryoSleep|Cabin|Group|Surname|Total|Deck|Side|RoomService|FoodCourt|Spa|VRDeck|ShoppingMall|Transported\\\" /tmp/gusthema_tfdf.txt /tmp/samuel_guide.txt /tmp/arunklenin_fe.txt /tmp/odins0n_models.txt /tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt | head -n 260\"","aggregated_output":"[\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 315987,\n    \"title\": \"Some rules to fill NaNs\",\n    \"author\": \"Vincent Debout\",\n    \"author_username\": \"vdebout\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 99,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"I denote \\\"Children\\\", persons with age <= 12 years old.\\n\\nHere are some rules I identified to fill NaNs:\\n\\n- link between HomePlanet and CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on E, F,G\\n    Mars on D, E, F\\n    Europa on A, B, C, D, E, T\\n- persons in the same group all have the same CabinSide, possibly on different CabinDeck\\n- in groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are necessarily on CabinDeck:\\n   Earth on G\\n   Europa on B\\n   Mars on E or F\\n- for Europa groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are on deck B\\n- CabinNum are in increasing order of PassengerIdGroup for each (CabinDeck, CabinSide)\\n  => This is very useful but need a complex algorithm. All Cabins are occupied ! \\n- People in a group have the same HomePlanet\\n- Surnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- Children have no bill\\n- CryoSleep have no bill\\n- People not Children and not CryoSleep with no bill all have Destination TRAPPIST-1e\\n- link between HomePlanet, VIP (also Age and CryoSleep):\\n   Earth no VIP\\n   Mars VIP have Age >= 18 and no CryoSleep and never goes to \\\"55 Cancri e\\\"\\n   Europa VIP have Age >= 25\\n- Europa with Age < 25 never goes to \\\"PSO J318.5-22\\\"\\n- Mars children are all transported\\n\\nApproximative rules (with some exceptions):\\n- Firstnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- ToTal bill has minimum per HomePlanet and CabinDeck (Earth is around 300, Mars 400 and Europa 1000), be careful when filling with median\\n\\n\\nPlease let me know if you identify additionnal rules\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/315987\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-03-30T16:58:04.683729200Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-05-01T03:32:59.423333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023635Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 332081,\n    \"title\": \"A Summary of all top discussion posts\",\n    \"author\": \"The Devastator\",\n    \"author_username\": \"thedevastator\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 26,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"## A Summary of all top discussion posts\\nBelow is a summary of all the top discussion posts of this competition so far. \\nMade by myself. \\n_____\\n\\n\\n[Make the best use of \\\"Deck\\\" feature](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310238) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- From the comments:\\n- I think the idea is to create a new feature that is 1 if the deck is safe and 0 if it is dangerous.\\n\\n[\\\"Gender\\\" didn't help me](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310239) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- Adding gender as a feature didn't help the author's model.\\n\\n[Spaceship Titanic Compare BaseModels EveryBody Get Insight!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309535)\\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\nThe author used pycaret to compere many models to try and find the best one. These were the results:\\n\\n![](https://i.ibb.co/26xKhJd/2022-02-24-094651.jpg)\\n\\n**Top 5 Models**\\n- LightGBM - 79.1%\\n- GradientBoostingClassifier - 79.6%\\n- AdaBoostClassifier - 79.4%\\n- RandomForest - 79.2%\\n- CatBoost - 79.6%\\n\\n[Question - How to deal with this kind of distribution ?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310009) \\nby [kartik2khandelwal](kartik2khandelwal)\\n\\n- The author was looking at the distribution of some of the features and asked for guidance about dealing with such a distribution.\\n\\n**Options proposed**\\n- **Remove Outliers** - but this will result in less data\\n- **Perform some transformation technique** - log, sqrt, boxcox and so on\\u2026\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** by putting all the outliers as 0 and other data as 1 - may leads to less information.\\n\\n**From the comments**\\n\\n- **Remove Outliers** - I would advise not to do so. Usually, if we remove outliers it is because we make the hypothesis that the event is due to some kind of artifact (a wrong record). But here, people paying a lot is not a wrong record and it could actually be valuable data.\\n- **Perform some transformation** - Every variable is not meant to be normally distributed. I think we can even expect this variable to be distributed as shown as we would expect only a few amounts of people to be able to spend that much. If you use log transform, for example, you will only compress your data and lose most of the value it holds. Except if you need to approximate a normal distribution for analysis purposes, or because you need to satisfy the normal distribution hypothesis for one of your processing steps, I would suggest not to.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** - As discussed previously, we can't really talk of outliers here. An outlier is a record that seems abnormal based on the hypothesis of the distribution it follows. So, I would suggest not applying this categorical transformation either.\\n\\n- **Perform some transformation** One could use a non-parametric estimator, such as decision trees or developments thereof, such as RandomForest, XGBoost, or HistGradientBoostingClassifier etc. thus obviating the need to transform the features to become Gaussian.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** Rather than actually replacing the feature as a categorical variable, create a new additional feature as a categorical variable, perhaps with something like\\n\\n- `df['food_spending'] = np.where(df['FoodCourt'] > 1000, 'yes', 'no')`\\n\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] High cardinality &amp; High correlation](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309513) \\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\nThe author is sharing some findings of EDA:\\n\\n- `PassengerId` has a high cardinality: 8693 distinct values\\n- `Cabin` has a high cardinality: 6560 distinct values\\n- `Name` has a high cardinality: 8473 distinct values\\n- `FoodCourt` is highly correlated with VRDeck`\\n- `CryoSleep` is highly correlated with `Transported`\\n- `HomePlanet` is highly correlated with `Destination`\\n\\n[Tip - Don't forget about the Cabin! \\ud83d\\udcc8](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309693)\\nby [alexteboul](alexteboul)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"For a slight **increase in accuracy**, don't drop the `Cabin` column entirely from your modeling.\\\"\\n\\n**For Example**\\n```python\\n# split column and add new columns to df\\ntrain[['Deck', 'Num', 'Side']] = train['Cabin'].str.split('/', expand=True)\\n# display the dataframe\\ntrain.head()\\n```\\n- [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/alexteboul/space-titanic-eda-models-lb-0-799l)\\n\\n[How to Choose OneHotEncoding between LabelEncoding? I'll Answer!! (EDA Tip)](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309803) \\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\n- From the post:\\n\\n**We apply One-Hot Encoding when:**\\n\\n- The Categorical feature is not ordinal\\n- The number of categorical features is less so one-hot encoding can be effectively applied\\n\\n**We apply Label Encoding when:**\\n- The categorical feature is ordinal (like Primary school, high school)\\n- The number of categories is quite large as one-hot encoding can lead to high memory consumption\\n\\nThe author also shared a public [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/kalelpark/spaceship-titanic-solutions-for-beginner)\\n\\n[Might be a good way to fill some missing  value?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310574) \\nby [gargantuar](gargantuar)\\n\\n- Found that for the passenger when the first part of the PassengerId is same ,the Homeplanet ,Cabin are also same.\\n- So, we can fill some missing value of these two values(about 50 in total 200),that might be able to improve the data quality.\\n\\n[Adding GENDER Feature based on NAME column](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309664) \\nby [sardorabdirayimov](sardorabdirayimov)\\n\\n- The notebook uses an [external web page](https://www.gpeters.com/names/baby-names.php) to identify gender based on the name\\n- Also: `Name` column in the dataset definitely helps to identify `gender`, `family`, `nationality` , `personality`\\n\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\udccc EDA\\ud83d\\udcc8 + FE\\ud83d\\udd25 + Comparison\\u2696\\ufe0f + Pseudo\\ud83c\\udfad](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309626) \\nby [hasanbasriakcay](hasanbasriakcay)\\n\\n- **Shared multiple notebooks:**\\n- [EDA](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-eda-fe-baseline)\\n- [Model Comparison](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pycaret-model-comparisons)\\n- [Pseudo Labeling](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pseudo-labels-stacking)\\n\\n[Cabin Feature is more IMPORTANT than you believe](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/319152)\\nby [javigallego](javigallego)\\n\\n- Sharing a code snippet for splitting the Cabin feature into 3 new features.\\n```python\\ndef split_Cabin(df):\\n    df['Deck'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[0]\\n    df['Number'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[1]\\n    df['Side'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[2]\\n    df.pop('Cabin')\\n    return df\\n```\\n\\n[Feature engineering results](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768)\\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n**Sharing the results of Feature Engineering:**\\n- drop VIP feature - 0.02% increase\\n- create an expenditure feature that sums the total money spent across the 5 amenities - 0.5% increase\\n- create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (RoomService, \\u2026,VRDeck) - 4.7% decrease\\n- create a cabin deck feature (A,B,\\u2026,T) - 0.35% increase\\n- create a cabin side feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase\\n- create a group size feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase\\n- create a no spending binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0 otherwise - 0.2% increase\\n- Create a solo feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase\\n- Create cabin region features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see here for details) - 0.2% increase-\\n- create a family size feature from last name - 0.0% change\\n- create binary age features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase\\n- same as above but drop the age column - 0.4% drop\\n\\n**Conclusions:**\\n- create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very helpful\\n- group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit\\n\\n[full notebook here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide)\\n\\n[Cabin number chunking](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379) \\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"It seems that the cabin number is chunked into groups of 300 cabins, and within each group the target distribution is a little bit different.\\\"\\n![](https://i.postimg.cc/NjpRsTXT/Cabin-number-distribution.png)\\n\\n\\n[Speed up your kernel using Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314402) \\nby [lordozvlad](lordozvlad)\\n\\n-From the post: \\\"If you want to speed up your kernel you can use Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn!\\\"\\n```python\\n!pip install scikit-learn-intelex\\n```\\n- [notebook:  Introduction to scikit-learn-intelex](https://www.kaggle.com/lordozvlad/introduction-to-scikit-learn-intelex/notebook)\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\ude80 Spaceship Titanic 0.79962 \\ud83d\\ude80](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312497) \\nby [rocklen](rocklen)\\n\\n- Sharing a [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/code/rocklen/spaceship-titanic-2-0-80079) with a score of 0.79962 using XGBoost + Randomized Search\\n\\n[Random Forest Perform significantly better in some cases than XGBoost](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314044)\\nby [shivamnegi1993](shivamnegi1993)\\n\\n- Random Forest is performing better than XGBoost in some cases.\\n- Check cases on the original thread.\\n\\n[Some rules to fill NaNs](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/315987) \\nby [vdebout](vdebout)\\n\\n- The author shared some hardcoded rules to fill NaNs.\\n\\n- link between HomePlanet and CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on E, F,G\\n    Mars on D, E, F\\n    Europa on A, B, C, D, E, T\\n- persons in the same group all have the same CabinSide, possibly on different CabinDeck\\n    in groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are necessarily on CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on G\\n    Europa on B\\n    Mars on E or F\\n- for Europa groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are on deck B\\n- CabinNum are in increasing order of PassengerIdGroup for each (CabinDeck, CabinSide) => This is very useful but need a complex algorithm. All Cabins are occupied !\\n- People in a group have the same HomePlanet\\n- Surnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- Children have no bill\\n- CryoSleep have no bill\\n- People not Children and not CryoSleep with no bill all have Destination TRAPPIST-1e\\n- link between HomePlanet, VIP (also Age and CryoSleep):\\n    Earth no VIP\\n    Mars VIP have Age >= 18 and no CryoSleep and never goes to \\\"55 Cancri e\\\"\\n    Europa VIP have Age >= 25\\n    Europa with Age < 25 never goes to \\\"PSO J318.5-22\\\"\\n    Mars children are all transported\\n\\n**Approximative rules (with some exceptions):**\\n- Firstnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- ToTal bill has minimum per HomePlanet and CabinDeck (Earth is around 300, Mars 400 and Europa 1000), be careful when filling with median\\n\\n\\n[Tip. Increase your score!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312173) \\nby [michael6141](michael6141)\\n\\n- Sharing a tip to increase your score: \\\"Try to average received probabilities on each validation split (list(probabilities)/len(probabilities)), predict_proba may help you. Averaging the model is a powerful tool to get a high validation score.\\\"\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] Missing Values](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309514)\\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\n- Age has 179 (2.1%) missing values\\n- Destination has 182 (2.1%) missing values\\n- FoodCourt has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- HomePlanet has 201 (2.3%) missing values\\n- Spa has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VIP has 203 (2.3%) missing values\\n- RoomService has 181 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VRDeck has 188 (2.2%) missing values\\n- Name has 200 (2.3%) missing values\\n- From the post:\\n- Cabin has 199 (2.3%) missing values\\n- ShoppingMall has 208 (2.4%) missing values\\n- CryoSleep has 217 (2.5%) missing values\\n\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/rishirajacharya/spaceship-titanic-detailed) about the missing values in the dataset.\\n\\n[[Spaceship Titanic] TensorFlow Extended - Towards ML Engineering ](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/328882)\\nby [usharengaraju](usharengaraju)\\n\\n- Sharing in depth analysis of the dataset using TensorFlow.\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/harshjain123/time-series-arima-sarima) about the following time series concepts:\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/332081\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-06-20T09:06:34.291829800Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2022-06-22T15:28:53.153333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023747Z\"\n  }\n]\n[\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309323,\n    \"title\": \"Welcome to the Spaceship Titanic!\",\n    \"author\": \"Ryan Holbrook\",\n    \"author_username\": \"ryanholbrook\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"STAFF\",\n    \"votes\": 220,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Welcome to the **Spaceship Titanic**!\\n\\nThe dataset is a bit bigger and the features a bit more complex, but this competition has everything you love about the original [**Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster**](https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic) -- this time *in space*!\\n\\nThere's a lot to discover in this dataset. Check out some of our [free courses](https://www.kaggle.com/learn) if you'd like to brush up on the fundamentals:\\n- [Python](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/python) for first steps with programming\\n- [Intro to Machine Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intro-to-machine-learning) for learning what it's all about\\n- [Pandas](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/pandas) on using Python's most popular library for manipulating tabular data\\n- [Intermediate Machine Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intermediate-machine-learning) on essential competition skills like categorical encoding and cross-validation\\n- [Data Visualization](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/data-visualization) for discovering relationships in the dataset\\n- [Feature Engineering](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/feature-engineering) on how to improve performance by creating more informative inputs\\n- [Intro to Deep Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intro-to-deep-learning) to discover neural networks\\n\\nBe sure to share your discoveries with a public notebook or here in the discussion forum.\\n\\nHappy Kaggling!\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309323\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-22T22:22:39.047565300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-25T13:49:41.816666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023598Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 316768,\n    \"title\": \"Feature engineering results\",\n    \"author\": \"Samuel Cortinhas\",\n    \"author_username\": \"samuelcortinhas\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 55,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Here is a summary of the **feature engineering** I have tried so far and the results I got on the test set. The baseline I used can be found in my notebook [here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide). All I did was add/drop 1 feature at a time and see how the final score changed.\\n\\n* drop **VIP** feature - 0.02% increase\\n* create an **expenditure** feature that sums the total money spent across the 5 amenities - 0.5% increase\\n* create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (**RoomService**, ...,**VRDeck**) - 4.7% decrease\\n* create a **cabin deck** feature (A,B,...,T) - 0.35% increase\\n* create a **cabin side** feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase \\n* create a **group size** feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase\\n* create a **no spending** binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0 otherwise - 0.2% increase\\n* Create a **solo** feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase\\n* Create **cabin region** features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see [here](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379) for details) - 0.2% increase\\n* create a **family size** feature from last name - 0.0% change\\n* create binary **age** features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase\\n* same as above but drop the **age** column - 0.4% drop\\n\\n**Conclusions:**\\n* create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very helpful\\n* group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit\\n\\nDo you agree? What feature engineering have you tried and did it improve your score?\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-04-03T18:24:50.078984100Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-06-10T04:03:09.240Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023671Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 332081,\n    \"title\": \"A Summary of all top discussion posts\",\n    \"author\": \"The Devastator\",\n    \"author_username\": \"thedevastator\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 26,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"## A Summary of all top discussion posts\\nBelow is a summary of all the top discussion posts of this competition so far. \\nMade by myself. \\n_____\\n\\n\\n[Make the best use of \\\"Deck\\\" feature](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310238) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- From the comments:\\n- I think the idea is to create a new feature that is 1 if the deck is safe and 0 if it is dangerous.\\n\\n[\\\"Gender\\\" didn't help me](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310239) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- Adding gender as a feature didn't help the author's model.\\n\\n[Spaceship Titanic Compare BaseModels EveryBody Get Insight!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309535)\\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\nThe author used pycaret to compere many models to try and find the best one. These were the results:\\n\\n![](https://i.ibb.co/26xKhJd/2022-02-24-094651.jpg)\\n\\n**Top 5 Models**\\n- LightGBM - 79.1%\\n- GradientBoostingClassifier - 79.6%\\n- AdaBoostClassifier - 79.4%\\n- RandomForest - 79.2%\\n- CatBoost - 79.6%\\n\\n[Question - How to deal with this kind of distribution ?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310009) \\nby [kartik2khandelwal](kartik2khandelwal)\\n\\n- The author was looking at the distribution of some of the features and asked for guidance about dealing with such a distribution.\\n\\n**Options proposed**\\n- **Remove Outliers** - but this will result in less data\\n- **Perform some transformation technique** - log, sqrt, boxcox and so on\\u2026\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** by putting all the outliers as 0 and other data as 1 - may leads to less information.\\n\\n**From the comments**\\n\\n- **Remove Outliers** - I would advise not to do so. Usually, if we remove outliers it is because we make the hypothesis that the event is due to some kind of artifact (a wrong record). But here, people paying a lot is not a wrong record and it could actually be valuable data.\\n- **Perform some transformation** - Every variable is not meant to be normally distributed. I think we can even expect this variable to be distributed as shown as we would expect only a few amounts of people to be able to spend that much. If you use log transform, for example, you will only compress your data and lose most of the value it holds. Except if you need to approximate a normal distribution for analysis purposes, or because you need to satisfy the normal distribution hypothesis for one of your processing steps, I would suggest not to.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** - As discussed previously, we can't really talk of outliers here. An outlier is a record that seems abnormal based on the hypothesis of the distribution it follows. So, I would suggest not applying this categorical transformation either.\\n\\n- **Perform some transformation** One could use a non-parametric estimator, such as decision trees or developments thereof, such as RandomForest, XGBoost, or HistGradientBoostingClassifier etc. thus obviating the need to transform the features to become Gaussian.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** Rather than actually replacing the feature as a categorical variable, create a new additional feature as a categorical variable, perhaps with something like\\n\\n- `df['food_spending'] = np.where(df['FoodCourt'] > 1000, 'yes', 'no')`\\n\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] High cardinality &amp; High correlation](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309513) \\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\nThe author is sharing some findings of EDA:\\n\\n- `PassengerId` has a high cardinality: 8693 distinct values\\n- `Cabin` has a high cardinality: 6560 distinct values\\n- `Name` has a high cardinality: 8473 distinct values\\n- `FoodCourt` is highly correlated with VRDeck`\\n- `CryoSleep` is highly correlated with `Transported`\\n- `HomePlanet` is highly correlated with `Destination`\\n\\n[Tip - Don't forget about the Cabin! \\ud83d\\udcc8](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309693)\\nby [alexteboul](alexteboul)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"For a slight **increase in accuracy**, don't drop the `Cabin` column entirely from your modeling.\\\"\\n\\n**For Example**\\n```python\\n# split column and add new columns to df\\ntrain[['Deck', 'Num', 'Side']] = train['Cabin'].str.split('/', expand=True)\\n# display the dataframe\\ntrain.head()\\n```\\n- [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/alexteboul/space-titanic-eda-models-lb-0-799l)\\n\\n[How to Choose OneHotEncoding between LabelEncoding? I'll Answer!! (EDA Tip)](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309803) \\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\n- From the post:\\n\\n**We apply One-Hot Encoding when:**\\n\\n- The Categorical feature is not ordinal\\n- The number of categorical features is less so one-hot encoding can be effectively applied\\n\\n**We apply Label Encoding when:**\\n- The categorical feature is ordinal (like Primary school, high school)\\n- The number of categories is quite large as one-hot encoding can lead to high memory consumption\\n\\nThe author also shared a public [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/kalelpark/spaceship-titanic-solutions-for-beginner)\\n\\n[Might be a good way to fill some missing  value?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310574) \\nby [gargantuar](gargantuar)\\n\\n- Found that for the passenger when the first part of the PassengerId is same ,the Homeplanet ,Cabin are also same.\\n- So, we can fill some missing value of these two values(about 50 in total 200),that might be able to improve the data quality.\\n\\n[Adding GENDER Feature based on NAME column](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309664) \\nby [sardorabdirayimov](sardorabdirayimov)\\n\\n- The notebook uses an [external web page](https://www.gpeters.com/names/baby-names.php) to identify gender based on the name\\n- Also: `Name` column in the dataset definitely helps to identify `gender`, `family`, `nationality` , `personality`\\n\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\udccc EDA\\ud83d\\udcc8 + FE\\ud83d\\udd25 + Comparison\\u2696\\ufe0f + Pseudo\\ud83c\\udfad](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309626) \\nby [hasanbasriakcay](hasanbasriakcay)\\n\\n- **Shared multiple notebooks:**\\n- [EDA](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-eda-fe-baseline)\\n- [Model Comparison](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pycaret-model-comparisons)\\n- [Pseudo Labeling](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pseudo-labels-stacking)\\n\\n[Cabin Feature is more IMPORTANT than you believe](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/319152)\\nby [javigallego](javigallego)\\n\\n- Sharing a code snippet for splitting the Cabin feature into 3 new features.\\n```python\\ndef split_Cabin(df):\\n    df['Deck'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[0]\\n    df['Number'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[1]\\n    df['Side'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[2]\\n    df.pop('Cabin')\\n    return df\\n```\\n\\n[Feature engineering results](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768)\\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n**Sharing the results of Feature Engineering:**\\n- drop VIP feature - 0.02% increase\\n- create an expenditure feature that sums the total money spent across the 5 amenities - 0.5% increase\\n- create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (RoomService, \\u2026,VRDeck) - 4.7% decrease\\n- create a cabin deck feature (A,B,\\u2026,T) - 0.35% increase\\n- create a cabin side feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase\\n- create a group size feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase\\n- create a no spending binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0 otherwise - 0.2% increase\\n- Create a solo feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase\\n- Create cabin region features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see here for details) - 0.2% increase-\\n- create a family size feature from last name - 0.0% change\\n- create binary age features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase\\n- same as above but drop the age column - 0.4% drop\\n\\n**Conclusions:**\\n- create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very helpful\\n- group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit\\n\\n[full notebook here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide)\\n\\n[Cabin number chunking](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379) \\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"It seems that the cabin number is chunked into groups of 300 cabins, and within each group the target distribution is a little bit different.\\\"\\n![](https://i.postimg.cc/NjpRsTXT/Cabin-number-distribution.png)\\n\\n\\n[Speed up your kernel using Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314402) \\nby [lordozvlad](lordozvlad)\\n\\n-From the post: \\\"If you want to speed up your kernel you can use Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn!\\\"\\n```python\\n!pip install scikit-learn-intelex\\n```\\n- [notebook:  Introduction to scikit-learn-intelex](https://www.kaggle.com/lordozvlad/introduction-to-scikit-learn-intelex/notebook)\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\ude80 Spaceship Titanic 0.79962 \\ud83d\\ude80](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312497) \\nby [rocklen](rocklen)\\n\\n- Sharing a [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/code/rocklen/spaceship-titanic-2-0-80079) with a score of 0.79962 using XGBoost + Randomized Search\\n\\n[Random Forest Perform significantly better in some cases than XGBoost](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314044)\\nby [shivamnegi1993](shivamnegi1993)\\n\\n- Random Forest is performing better than XGBoost in some cases.\\n- Check cases on the original thread.\\n\\n[Some rules to fill NaNs](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/315987) \\nby [vdebout](vdebout)\\n\\n- The author shared some hardcoded rules to fill NaNs.\\n\\n- link between HomePlanet and CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on E, F,G\\n    Mars on D, E, F\\n    Europa on A, B, C, D, E, T\\n- persons in the same group all have the same CabinSide, possibly on different CabinDeck\\n    in groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are necessarily on CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on G\\n    Europa on B\\n    Mars on E or F\\n- for Europa groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are on deck B\\n- CabinNum are in increasing order of PassengerIdGroup for each (CabinDeck, CabinSide) => This is very useful but need a complex algorithm. All Cabins are occupied !\\n- People in a group have the same HomePlanet\\n- Surnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- Children have no bill\\n- CryoSleep have no bill\\n- People not Children and not CryoSleep with no bill all have Destination TRAPPIST-1e\\n- link between HomePlanet, VIP (also Age and CryoSleep):\\n    Earth no VIP\\n    Mars VIP have Age >= 18 and no CryoSleep and never goes to \\\"55 Cancri e\\\"\\n    Europa VIP have Age >= 25\\n    Europa with Age < 25 never goes to \\\"PSO J318.5-22\\\"\\n    Mars children are all transported\\n\\n**Approximative rules (with some exceptions):**\\n- Firstnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- ToTal bill has minimum per HomePlanet and CabinDeck (Earth is around 300, Mars 400 and Europa 1000), be careful when filling with median\\n\\n\\n[Tip. Increase your score!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312173) \\nby [michael6141](michael6141)\\n\\n- Sharing a tip to increase your score: \\\"Try to average received probabilities on each validation split (list(probabilities)/len(probabilities)), predict_proba may help you. Averaging the model is a powerful tool to get a high validation score.\\\"\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] Missing Values](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309514)\\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\n- Age has 179 (2.1%) missing values\\n- Destination has 182 (2.1%) missing values\\n- FoodCourt has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- HomePlanet has 201 (2.3%) missing values\\n- Spa has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VIP has 203 (2.3%) missing values\\n- RoomService has 181 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VRDeck has 188 (2.2%) missing values\\n- Name has 200 (2.3%) missing values\\n- From the post:\\n- Cabin has 199 (2.3%) missing values\\n- ShoppingMall has 208 (2.4%) missing values\\n- CryoSleep has 217 (2.5%) missing values\\n\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/rishirajacharya/spaceship-titanic-detailed) about the missing values in the dataset.\\n\\n[[Spaceship Titanic] TensorFlow Extended - Towards ML Engineering ](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/328882)\\nby [usharengaraju](usharengaraju)\\n\\n- Sharing in depth analysis of the dataset using TensorFlow.\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/harshjain123/time-series-arima-sarima) about the following time series concepts:\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/332081\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-06-20T09:06:34.291829800Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2022-06-22T15:28:53.153333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023747Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309626,\n    \"title\": \"\\ud83d\\udccc EDA\\ud83d\\udcc8 + FE\\ud83d\\udd25 + Comparison\\u2696\\ufe0f + Pseudo\\ud83c\\udfad\",\n    \"author\": \"Hasan Basri Ak\\u00e7ay\",\n    \"author_username\": \"hasanbasriakcay\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 15,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Hi all,\\n\\nI prepared three notebooks for you. In the first [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-eda-fe-baseline), I did exploratory data analysis and feature engineering. In the second [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pycaret-model-comparisons), I compared machine learning models and in the third [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pseudo-labels-stacking), I did pseudo labeling for better Leaderboard scores. \\n\\n1.  [EDA Notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-eda-fe-baseline)\\n2. [Model Comparisons Notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pycaret-model-comparisons)\\n3. [Pseudo Labels Notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pseudo-labels-stacking)\\n\\nKindly upvote if you find it useful \\ud83d\\ude0a\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309626\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-24T13:58:31.346542Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-15T11:41:08.910Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023853Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 328882,\n    \"title\": \"[Spaceship Titanic] TensorFlow Extended - Towards ML Engineering \",\n    \"author\": \"Tensor Girl\",\n    \"author_username\": \"usharengaraju\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 13,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"\\nTensorFlow Extended (TFX) is used to create machine learning pipelines. It is open-source and is used by many large companies to put their machine learning model into production.\\n\\n![im](https://i.imgur.com/Npjr3NK.png)\\n\\n\\n**Pipeline :**\\nA TFX pipeline is used to implement an ML pipeline which remains intact for the entire lifetime of the product. They are built using tfx components. \\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/z3mMdts.png)\\n\\n**Metadata store**-\\n\\nIt is a single place to manage all the ML metadata about experiments, artifacts, models, and pipelines.\\nA store consists of - \\nDefinitions of artifacts and their properties\\nExecution records of components\\nLineage tracking across all executions\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/DwDEvHq.png)\\n\\n**TFX Orchestrator**-\\nAn Orchestrator is a system where you can execute pipeline runs. Apache airflow, kubeflow are used as orchestrators. Dagrunner is used to refer to an implementation that supports orchestrator.\\n\\n**Components**-\\nA component is used to implement a part of the ML pipeline. ML pipeline consists of many such components. Components are composed of:\\n\\ncomponent specification- Defines the component's input, output and required parameters.\\nexecutor- Implements the code in that component\\ncomponent interface- Contains component specification and executor\\n \\nExplaining each component here-\\n\\n**ExampleGen**- This component ingests data into the pipelines. It takes external files (in formats such as CSV, TFRecord, BigQuery etc),partitions and shuffles it, to generate the Examples file. \\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/hrb82Ev.png)\\n\\n**StatisticsGen**-\\nIt generates features statistics over Example data and releases data statistics for other pipeline components.\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/Ym9pOZd.png)\\n\\n**SchemaGen**\\nSchema provides a description of input data. SchemaGen automatically generates a schema from the training data and provides detail about the features, their allowed values and data types for feature values.\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/MySRzxs.png)\\n\\n**ExampleValidator**\\nIt finds anomalies in training and serving data by comparing data statistics computed by the StatisticsGen pipeline component against a schema. For example: \\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/FMi2ZWn.png)\\n\\n**Transform**\\nIt performs feature engineering on Example data and releases both SavedModel as well as statistics on both pre-transform and post-transform data.\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/R1OYqkV.png)\\n\\n**Trainer**\\nTrainer is used to train models using tensorflow.\\nIt takes Examples data, logic for training the data and protobuf definition for trainargs and eval argos. It releases a model for inference and maybe another one for evaluation\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/u6NqxPJ.png)\\n\\n**Evaluator**\\nIt performs analysis on the training results for the models to access overall model quality and track performance over time. It validates if the model can be pushed for production.\\nIf the new model's metrics meet the baseline model requirements, the model is said to be \\\"blessed\\\", and is pushed to production.\\n\\n![](https://i.imgur.com/9dXiq4y.png)\\n\\n**Pusher**\\nIT is used to push a validated model to a deployment. \\n \\nThe Pusher component pushes a validated model to a deployment target during model training . Pusher decides to push or not based on the blessings from the other components.\\nEvaluator blesses the model if it is \\\"good enough\\\" to be pushed to production.\\nInfraValidator blesses the model if the model is mechanically servable in a production environment.\\nA Pusher component consumes a trained model in SavedModel format, and outputs  the same SavedModel, along with versioning metadata.\\n \\n ![](https://i.imgur.com/rqyuCgC.png)\\u00b7        \\n \\n\\nThe ExampleGen TFX Pipeline component ingests data into TFX pipelines by consuming external data sources such as CSV, TFRecord, Avro, Parquet and BigQuery to generate Examples( tf.Example records, tf.SequenceExample records, or proto format) which will be read by other TFX components. \\nExampleGen and Other Components\\nExampleGen provides data to components that make use of the TensorFlow Data Validation library, such as SchemaGen, StatisticsGen, and Example Validator. It also provides data to Transform, which makes use of the TensorFlow Transform library, and ultimately to deployment targets during inference.\\n \\n\\n\\n\\n**Kindly restart the colab runtime after TFX installation to run without errors**\\n\\nBelow is tutorial series on TensorFlow Extended using SpaceShip Titanic Dataset\\n\\nTFX Starter Pipeline\\n\\nhttps://colab.research.google.com/drive/1KCLbxVItQpAITemVrjPs64yX3-RS1J--?usp=sharing\\n\\n\\nTFX Interactive :\\n\\nhttps://colab.research.google.com/drive/1kj65CT3d4ninQhJT_NXj5yI5t6vuZ5fa?usp=sharing\\n\\nTFMA\\n\\nhttps://colab.research.google.com/drive/1tTG80-wgWl5nnCc5NPqeGTjqdhAypMDB?usp=sharing\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nAttribution :\\n\\nhttps://www.tensorflow.org/tfx\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/328882\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-06-03T12:38:17.758300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-16T16:55:05.993333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234598Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 552340,\n    \"title\": \"Rank 8 approach - simple ML models and Optuna ensemble\",\n    \"author\": \"Ravi Ramakrishnan\",\n    \"author_username\": \"ravi20076\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 12,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Hello all,\\n\\nMy 8th place kernels are public and are available at the below links-\\n1. https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravi20076/spaceshiptitanic-models/notebook\\n2. https://www.kaggle.com/code/ravi20076/spaceshiptitanic-blending\\n\\n# Approach\\n\\n## Feature engineering\\nThanks to @arunklenin for the FE notebook from the other Spaceship Titanic competition. Kernel is [here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/arunklenin/space-titanic-eda-advanced-feature-engineering)\\n\\n## Model training\\n1. I used a stratified 10-fold CV scheme \\n2. I resorted to a gamut of gbdt models including Catboost, LightGBM and XgBoost along with scikit-learn models like Random Forest and Histogram Gradient Boosting Classifier for the pipeline\\n\\n## Blending \\nI used Optuna to blend the results of the individual models\\n\\n## Areas of improvement \\n1. I could have used AutoML tools \\n2. I could have experimented with NNs\\n3. Better blending strategies may have created a better result \\n\\n# Concluding remarks \\nThanks to @carlmcbrideellis for the competition.\\nHappy learning and best regards!\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/552340\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2024-12-19T06:40:23.576160600Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2024-12-25T17:02:37.453333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234606Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309664,\n    \"title\": \"Adding GENDER Feature based on NAME column\",\n    \"author\": \"Sardor Abdirayimov\",\n    \"author_username\": \"sardorabdirayimov\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"EXPERT\",\n    \"votes\": 10,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Dear Kagglers,\\nI am happy to participate in the current competition, which is very interesting and useful for practicing. \\nMissing values in the dataset make the competition even attractive. \\n`Feature Engineering` is art \\ud83c\\udfa8 in Data Science!\\nAs an example, I want to share my thoughts to identify genders, based on the first names of the people.\\nI search the internet and find some APIs that help to identify with high accuracy, but those APIs are limited. For example, in one API, I can use API 1000 times a day. However, I have a dataset of more than 8k. \\nAfter that, I find a simple web page which identifies gender based on the name: Visit the web page if interested: https://www.gpeters.com/names/baby-names.php\\nThe benefits of the web page are free to access and have no limitations.\\nThe disadvantages of the web page are that it does not provide API service and comparatively slowness.\\nSome APIs require signing up in order to use their tools. For example, https://gender-api.com \\nTo sum up, `Name` column in the dataset definitely helps to identify `gender`, `family`, `nationality` , `personality`, and other key features to improve accuracy of the MLAs.\\nShare your ideas about your ideas in `Feature engineering` \",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309664\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-24T17:36:19.192762100Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-16T16:57:23.880Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234687Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 351953,\n    \"title\": \"New Blog Series: My Journey on the Spaceship Titanic\",\n    \"author\": \"danb91\",\n    \"author_username\": \"danb91\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"EXPERT\",\n    \"votes\": 9,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Hello everyone,\\nI just published [the first of a series of blogs](https://medium.com/@bukowski.daniel/my-journey-on-the-spaceship-titanic-ddec757877a4) detailing my experience working with the Spaceship Titanic data set. During the past few weeks I have published four Spaceship Titanic notebooks, each of which has earned a bronze medal:\\n- [SpacshipTitanic Starter EDA, RF, Model Eval 80%](https://www.kaggle.com/code/danb91/spacshiptitanic-starter-eda-rf-model-eval-80): My first Spaceship Titanic notebook in which I perform EDA, pre-process the data, and train a Random Forest model. The EDA and preprocessing steps are the baseline for future notebooks, as is the accuracy of the random forest model.\\n- [\\ud83d\\ude80 Pipeline, RF, XGB, LGBM 80%+ Top 15% \\ud83d\\udd25](https://www.kaggle.com/code/danb91/pipeline-rf-xgb-lgbm-80-top-15): My second notebook where I refine the preprocessing steps and train XGBoost and LightGBM models, in addition to a Random Forest model. \\n- [\\ud83d\\ude80 RF, XGB, LGBM 81% with Optuna \\ud83d\\udd25](https://www.kaggle.com/code/danb91/rf-xgb-lgbm-81-with-optuna): My third notebook where I incorporate Optuna to optimize the hyperparameters for each of the Random forest, XGBoost, and LightGBM models.\\n- [\\ud83d\\ude80 Titanic: Better Imputation with KNN! \\ud83d\\udd25](https://www.kaggle.com/code/danb91/titanic-better-imputation-with-knn): My most recent notebook (as of this writing) where I use KNN for imputation and explore additional feature engineering techniques. \\n\\nGoing forward I plan to publish a blog about each of the notebooks above where I dig into my thinking and lessons learned. I also plan to update each of the above notebooks as I see opportunities (which I am sure there will be many). Additionally, I have several additional notebooks planned where I use the Spaceship Titanic data to explore other aspects of the machine learning workflow (better imputation and feature engineering, additional models, neural networks, etc...).\\n\\nI hope everyone finds these notebooks and the blogs useful! Please provide feedback or support here or in the notebooks themselves.\\n\\nGood luck!\\nDan\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/351953\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-09-12T13:17:57.932658800Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-17T14:51:18.766666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234705Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 567313,\n    \"title\": \"How to Get into the Top 100 in the Spaceship Titanic Competition?\",\n    \"author\": \"Yaroslav53\",\n    \"author_username\": \"yaroslav53\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 8,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"When I decided to participate in the **Spaceship Titanic** competition, my goal was not only to compete for a top position but also to expand my experience in applying fundamental machine learning techniques. I wanted to try as many different data processing and modeling techniques as possible to better understand the core approaches and methods commonly used in such challenges. \\ud83e\\uddd0\\nMy journey turned out to be quite productive, and in this post, I will share how I managed to get into the **top 100** solutions. If you are a beginner, I am sure you will find this experience valuable. I divided my work into several stages, each of which was implemented in a separate notebook. This approach helped me not only structure the process but also make it easier to track and fix errors.\\nThis is one of my first tips for beginners: if you have many ideas, break them down into separate parts \\u2014 it will make working and testing different approaches much easier.\\ud83d\\udca1\\n\\nFrom the very beginning, I decided to use only **basic machine learning methods**, avoiding deep learning and complex data encoding techniques. In the first stage of my work [spaceship_titanic_baseline](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/spaceship-titanic-baseline?scriptVersionId=171694491), I quickly explored the data: I checked what features were available and how they were distributed. Nothing unusual\\u2014just a standard data analysis process, from which I made a few initial assumptions. Then, I trained a simple model and recorded the result. And here\\u2019s the interesting part: my initial, simple solution didn\\u2019t differ much in quality from the more complex models I tried later.\\ud83d\\ude2f But I\\u2019ll get back to that later.\\n\\nIt\\u2019s worth noting that in this notebook, I used a few **simple yet useful custom functions** that might be helpful to others. Additionally, I practiced using **Kaggle Utility Scripts**\\u2014[kaggletoolkit](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/kaggletoolkit?scriptVersionId=210343237)\\n\\nNext, I proceeded with **data preparation** for further work [spaceship_titanic_main](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/spaceship-titanic-main?scriptVersionId=210822614). I created new features and processed the existing ones. One of the most interesting steps was generating a **\\\"gender\\\"** feature based on the passenger\\u2019s name.\\n\\nBy the way, the previously mentioned script includes functions for **parsing data**, which can be used to infer gender from a name. If anyone is interested, here\\u2019s [Gender_by_name_for_spaceship_titanic](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/yaroslav53/gender-by-name-for-spaceship-titanic/data), where I collected gender data based on names.\\n\\nAs a result, I managed to create **a wide range of new features**, and even a simple model **without hyperparameter tuning** showed a **decent result\\u2014Score 0.806177**. At this point, I could have stopped, picked a popular boosting algorithm, fine-tuned the parameters, and called it a day.\\n\\nBut I was curious to continue\\u2014and if you're still reading this, let\\u2019s keep going. \\ud83d\\ude80\\n\\nMy plan was to **train several different models** and then try to **combine them**. I started with SVC and kNN [SVM and kNN](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/svm-and-knn-spaceship-titanic?scriptVersionId=224242528).\\n\\nThis notebook might be **useful for beginners**\\ud83d\\ude0a, as it demonstrates basic data processing methods for these models. I also applied PCA (Principal Component Analysis). As expected, the results of these models were lower in quality compared to boosting, but I was able to significantly reduce the number of features without losing performance.\\n\\nIn this competition, feature reduction didn\\u2019t provide much advantage, but I still gained **valuable experience**.\\n\\nThen came the moment when I needed to work with more powerful models, and of course, my choice fell on **gradient boosting** [CatBoost and XGBoost](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/catboost-and-xgboost-spaceship-titanic?scriptVersionId=223756072).\\n\\nThis is where the real struggle began\\ud83d\\ude14. My expectations were high\\u2014I was already getting a **0.806177 score** with a **basic CatBoost**, and I thought that with proper hyperparameter tuning, I could push it to at least **0.82**.\\n\\nBut things didn\\u2019t go as planned. I tried **everything I knew**:\\n- *Generating new features*\\n- *Analyzing model results*\\n- *Handling anomalies*\\n- *Experimenting with model blending*\\n- *Hyperparameter optimization with Optuna*\\n\\nAnd yet, **the score remained almost the same**.\\ud83d\\ude11\\n\\nThe main challenge I faced was setting up **proper validation**. I\\u2019ll admit\\u2014I didn\\u2019t dive deep into the differences between the train and test datasets or check discussions from other participants on this topic. So, I\\u2019m not sure how common this issue was, but based on my observations, the **test data was noticeably different from the training data**\\u203c\\ufe0f\\n\\nWhen I finally paid attention to these differences, I decided to run **Adversarial Validation**\\u2014and sure enough, the **data distributions in the train and test sets didn\\u2019t match**.\\n\\nThis turned out to be the core difficulty of the competition: because of these differences, it was impossible to build a validation strategy that truly reflected how the model would perform on the test set. As a result, I kept improving my model\\u2019s **score on the training data**, but after submission, the result **remained almost unchanged**.\\n\\nBy the time I realized this issue, my **motivation and energy** to dive deep into **data processing**\\u2014and thus make the distributions more similar for proper validation\\u2014were already gone.\\ud83d\\ude36\\n\\nI tried to take a shortcut\\u2014tweaking the number of folds, changing splitting strategies, and experimenting with different cross-validation approaches, but **none of it worked**.\\n\\nIt became clear that achieving reliable validation required deliberate efforts to adjust the data distribution, reducing feature-space discrepancies. But at that point, I had no desire to go down that rabbit hole.\\n\\nSo, I decided to just **blend the models** and **work with what I had**, hoping for the best.\\ud83d\\ude0c\\n\\nI wrapped up the competition by attempting **model blending and stacking** [spaceship_titanic_final](https://www.kaggle.com/code/yaroslav53/spaceship-titanic-final?scriptVersionId=224988642).\\n\\nOnce again, I ran into the **same validation issue**, but I kept experimenting with different ensemble methods. I tried averaging both the final model predictions and their probabilities.\\n\\nFor **stacking**, I tested various approaches:\\n\\n- *Using both probabilities and predictions from base models as inputs*\\n- *Including different features from the original dataset*\\n- *Experimenting with different meta-models*\\n- *Tuning hyperparameters*\\n\\nBut **nothing worked**\\u2014the train score kept improving, while the test score dropped.\\n\\nIn the end, I managed to slightly improve my score, but ironically, it was thanks to one of the simplest methods\\u2014plain blending of predictions.\\n\\n**Final result: 0.80874.**\\n\\nWrapping up this story, I want to highlight that working on this competition gave me not only valuable experience but also **plenty of challenges**.\\n\\nI think everyone in machine learning has faced that frustrating moment when a model\\u2019s performance improves on the training set but stays the same on the test set. It\\u2019s definitely disappointing, but despite these setbacks, **participating in this competition was absolutely worth it.**\\n\\nFor beginners, Spaceship Titanic is an **excellent choice**: the dataset is simple and intuitive, and even without extensive experience in feature engineering, interesting ideas come to mind right away.\\ud83d\\udca1 Plus, working with a binary target makes model analysis and interpretation much easier. So, if you're looking for a learning-friendly competition, I can **highly recommend** this one.\\n\\nIf you're already participating and aiming for maximum performance, I\\u2019d suggest paying close attention to the differences between the feature distributions in the train and test datasets. Reducing these discrepancies using techniques like **Adversarial Validation** could be a game-changer.\\n\\nThank you for **reading this post!** I\\u2019d be happy if someone finds **something useful** in my work.\\n\\nAs you might have noticed, I put in a significant amount of effort, so there\\u2019s a chance I made mistakes or overlooked important details. Also, not all experiments I mentioned are included in the notebooks\\u2014if something didn\\u2019t improve the score, I simply **removed the code.**\\n\\nSee you in the next competitions\\u2014**good luck!** \\ud83d\\ude80\\ud83d\\ude0a\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/567313\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2025-03-09T16:06:42.046551500Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-03-13T12:35:53.846666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234721Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 442766,\n    \"title\": \"15 Tips before you start ! \",\n    \"author\": \"Thunder\",\n    \"author_username\": \"thunder7\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 8,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"\\n###  15 Tips for Beginners! \\ud83d\\udef3\\ufe0f\\n\\nHere are some tips to help beginners get started on this classic machine learning problem:\\n\\n1.  **Understand the Problem**. Familiarize yourself with the  [dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/data)  and its features. Understand what each column represents and the nature of the data (e.g., categorical, numerical). Also make sure to check out the excellent  [Overview](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic)  of the competition.\\n2.  **Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)**. Visualize and explore the data to gain insights. Use libraries like Matplotlib and Seaborn for data visualization. The Kaggle mini-course on  [Data Visualization](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/data-visualization)  covers this well. Check for missing values and decide on an appropriate strategy for handling them (e.g. imputation or removal). Check out the  [Data Cleaning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/data-cleaning)  course if needed.\\n3.  **Feature Engineering**. Create new features that might be informative for the prediction task. For example, you can extract titles from passenger names or create family size features. Encode categorical variables into numerical form using techniques like one-hot encoding or label encoding. Try the  [Feature Engineering](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/feature-engineering)  course if you want more practice.\\n4.  **Data Preprocessing**. Split your data into training and validation sets to evaluate your model's performance. Scale or normalize numerical features to ensure they have similar scales. Handle outliers if necessary (e.g., by winsorizing). The  [Intro to Machine Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intro-to-machine-learning)  course covers a lot of this.\\n5.  **Model Selection**. Start with simple models like logistic regression or Random Forest to establish a baseline. Experiment with different algorithms such as Gradient Boosting algorithms, Support Vector Machines, and neural networks. Tune hyperparameters using  [Optuna](https://optuna.org/)  and use techniques like cross-validation, covered in  [Intermediate Machine Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intermediate-machine-learning), to find the best model.\\n6.  **Model Evaluation**. Choose appropriate evaluation metrics for classification tasks (e.g., accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and understand what each of them mean). Consider the class imbalance in the target variable (i.e. survived vs. not survived) and use techniques like stratified sampling or weighted loss functions to handle any class imbalance.\\n7.  **Feature Importance**. Understand which features are the most important for your model's predictions. You can use feature importance scores provided by some algorithms (e.g.  [Random Forest](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/ensemble/plot_forest_importances.html)) or techniques like permutation importance.\\n8.  **Ensemble Methods**. Combine multiple models using ensemble methods (e.g., stacking, bagging, boosting) to potentially improve performance. This will be of great help in future more difficult competitions.\\n9.  **Cross-Validation**. Use cross-validation (CV) to assess your model's generalization performance and avoid overfitting. CV is covered in the  [Intermediate Machine Learning](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/intermediate-machine-learning)  course.\\n10.  **Regularization**. Apply regularization techniques (e.g., L1, L2 regularization) to prevent overfitting, especially when using complex models with a lot of parameters.\\n11.  **Interpretability**. Consider using methods like SHAP values or feature importance plots to interpret your model's predictions. Both are covered in the  [Machine Learning Explainability](https://www.kaggle.com/learn/machine-learning-explainability)  course.\\n12.  **Documentation**. Keep track of your experiments, hyperparameters, and CV results. Document your code and analysis for future iterations and reference.\\n13.  **Submission and Post-Processing**. Make predictions on the test dataset and prepare your submission for Kaggle. Be mindful of any post-processing steps you apply to your predictions, as Kaggle often has specific evaluation criteria.\\n14.  **Learn from the Community**. Explore the Kaggle  [Space Titanic Discussion Forum](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic)  and  [notebooks](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/code)  to learn from others who have worked on the Titanic dataset. You can gain valuable insights and tips from the community.\\n15.  **Iterate and Refine**. Don't be discouraged if your first model doesn't perform well. Machine learning is an iterative process, and you should continue to refine your model and approach.\\n\\nGood luck! \\ud83c\\udf40\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/442766\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2023-09-24T04:11:11.215315300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-12-17T12:50:09.600Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234745Z\"\n  }\n]\n[\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 315987,\n    \"title\": \"Some rules to fill NaNs\",\n    \"author\": \"Vincent Debout\",\n    \"author_username\": \"vdebout\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 99,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"I denote \\\"Children\\\", persons with age <= 12 years old.\\n\\nHere are some rules I identified to fill NaNs:\\n\\n- link between HomePlanet and CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on E, F,G\\n    Mars on D, E, F\\n    Europa on A, B, C, D, E, T\\n- persons in the same group all have the same CabinSide, possibly on different CabinDeck\\n- in groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are necessarily on CabinDeck:\\n   Earth on G\\n   Europa on B\\n   Mars on E or F\\n- for Europa groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are on deck B\\n- CabinNum are in increasing order of PassengerIdGroup for each (CabinDeck, CabinSide)\\n  => This is very useful but need a complex algorithm. All Cabins are occupied ! \\n- People in a group have the same HomePlanet\\n- Surnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- Children have no bill\\n- CryoSleep have no bill\\n- People not Children and not CryoSleep with no bill all have Destination TRAPPIST-1e\\n- link between HomePlanet, VIP (also Age and CryoSleep):\\n   Earth no VIP\\n   Mars VIP have Age >= 18 and no CryoSleep and never goes to \\\"55 Cancri e\\\"\\n   Europa VIP have Age >= 25\\n- Europa with Age < 25 never goes to \\\"PSO J318.5-22\\\"\\n- Mars children are all transported\\n\\nApproximative rules (with some exceptions):\\n- Firstnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- ToTal bill has minimum per HomePlanet and CabinDeck (Earth is around 300, Mars 400 and Europa 1000), be careful when filling with median\\n\\n\\nPlease let me know if you identify additionnal rules\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/315987\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-03-30T16:58:04.683729200Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-05-01T03:32:59.423333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023635Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 316768,\n    \"title\": \"Feature engineering results\",\n    \"author\": \"Samuel Cortinhas\",\n    \"author_username\": \"samuelcortinhas\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 55,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Here is a summary of the **feature engineering** I have tried so far and the results I got on the test set. The baseline I used can be found in my notebook [here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide). All I did was add/drop 1 feature at a time and see how the final score changed.\\n\\n* drop **VIP** feature - 0.02% increase\\n* create an **expenditure** feature that sums the total money spent across the 5 amenities - 0.5% increase\\n* create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (**RoomService**, ...,**VRDeck**) - 4.7% decrease\\n* create a **cabin deck** feature (A,B,...,T) - 0.35% increase\\n* create a **cabin side** feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase \\n* create a **group size** feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase\\n* create a **no spending** binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0 otherwise - 0.2% increase\\n* Create a **solo** feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase\\n* Create **cabin region** features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see [here](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379) for details) - 0.2% increase\\n* create a **family size** feature from last name - 0.0% change\\n* create binary **age** features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase\\n* same as above but drop the **age** column - 0.4% drop\\n\\n**Conclusions:**\\n* create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very helpful\\n* group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit\\n\\nDo you agree? What feature engineering have you tried and did it improve your score?\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-04-03T18:24:50.078984100Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-06-10T04:03:09.240Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023671Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309803,\n    \"title\": \"How to Choose OneHotEncoding between LabelEncoding? I'll Answer!! (EDA Tip)\",\n    \"author\": \"Wongi Park\",\n    \"author_username\": \"kalelpark\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 44,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"We apply One-Hot Encoding when:\\n1. The Categorical feature is not ordinal\\n2. The number of categorical features is less so one-hot encoding can be effectively applied\\n\\nWe apply Label Encoding when:\\n\\n1. The categorical feature is ordinal (like Primary school, high school)\\n2. The number of categories is quite large as one-hot encoding can lead to high memory consumption\\n<hr>\\n\\nOne-Hot-Encoding Feature\\n- HomePlanet\\n- CryoSleep\\n- Cabin (Side)\\n- Destination\\n- VIP\\n\\nLabel Encoding Feature\\n- Cabin(Deck)\\n- Name    (cause.2)   (many nuinque values)\\n\\n<hr>\\nWe can think about new Feature about Total bill!\\n\\nTotal Bill = 'RoomService' +  'FoodCourt' + 'ShoppingMall '+ 'Spa' + 'VRDeck'\\n* We need to deal with NaN values Before adding them.\\n(NaN values replace 0 beacuse,  It's most common in data.)\\n\\nIf you helpful, Don't forget vote!\\nModel tip : https://www.kaggle.com/c/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309535\\n\\nCode : https://www.kaggle.com/kalelpark/spaceship-titanic-solutions-for-beginner\\n(Code will be Update!)\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309803\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-25T16:17:53.392291300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-05-07T14:39:16.120Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023690Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309693,\n    \"title\": \"Tip - Don't forget about the Cabin! \\ud83d\\udcc8\",\n    \"author\": \"Alex Teboul\",\n    \"author_username\": \"alexteboul\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"EXPERT\",\n    \"votes\": 38,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"For a slight **increase in accuracy**, don't drop the **Cabin** column entirely from your modeling.\\n\\n**For example:**\\n```\\n# split column and add new columns to df\\ntrain[['Deck', 'Num', 'Side']] = train['Cabin'].str.split('/', expand=True)\\n# display the dataframe\\ntrain.head()\\n```\\n\\n[![Screen-Shot-2022-02-24-at-4-07-00-PM.png](https://i.postimg.cc/BQ8rqMQH/Screen-Shot-2022-02-24-at-4-07-00-PM.png)](https://postimg.cc/RNBsd1tZ)\\n\\n## [Notebook Link](https://www.kaggle.com/alexteboul/space-titanic-eda-models-lb-0-799l)\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309693\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-24T22:19:11.164984300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2024-07-08T14:13:09.266666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023712Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 332081,\n    \"title\": \"A Summary of all top discussion posts\",\n    \"author\": \"The Devastator\",\n    \"author_username\": \"thedevastator\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 26,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"## A Summary of all top discussion posts\\nBelow is a summary of all the top discussion posts of this competition so far. \\nMade by myself. \\n_____\\n\\n\\n[Make the best use of \\\"Deck\\\" feature](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310238) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- From the comments:\\n- I think the idea is to create a new feature that is 1 if the deck is safe and 0 if it is dangerous.\\n\\n[\\\"Gender\\\" didn't help me](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310239) \\nby [mostafaalaa123](mostafaalaa123)\\n\\n- Adding gender as a feature didn't help the author's model.\\n\\n[Spaceship Titanic Compare BaseModels EveryBody Get Insight!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309535)\\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\nThe author used pycaret to compere many models to try and find the best one. These were the results:\\n\\n![](https://i.ibb.co/26xKhJd/2022-02-24-094651.jpg)\\n\\n**Top 5 Models**\\n- LightGBM - 79.1%\\n- GradientBoostingClassifier - 79.6%\\n- AdaBoostClassifier - 79.4%\\n- RandomForest - 79.2%\\n- CatBoost - 79.6%\\n\\n[Question - How to deal with this kind of distribution ?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310009) \\nby [kartik2khandelwal](kartik2khandelwal)\\n\\n- The author was looking at the distribution of some of the features and asked for guidance about dealing with such a distribution.\\n\\n**Options proposed**\\n- **Remove Outliers** - but this will result in less data\\n- **Perform some transformation technique** - log, sqrt, boxcox and so on\\u2026\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** by putting all the outliers as 0 and other data as 1 - may leads to less information.\\n\\n**From the comments**\\n\\n- **Remove Outliers** - I would advise not to do so. Usually, if we remove outliers it is because we make the hypothesis that the event is due to some kind of artifact (a wrong record). But here, people paying a lot is not a wrong record and it could actually be valuable data.\\n- **Perform some transformation** - Every variable is not meant to be normally distributed. I think we can even expect this variable to be distributed as shown as we would expect only a few amounts of people to be able to spend that much. If you use log transform, for example, you will only compress your data and lose most of the value it holds. Except if you need to approximate a normal distribution for analysis purposes, or because you need to satisfy the normal distribution hypothesis for one of your processing steps, I would suggest not to.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** - As discussed previously, we can't really talk of outliers here. An outlier is a record that seems abnormal based on the hypothesis of the distribution it follows. So, I would suggest not applying this categorical transformation either.\\n\\n- **Perform some transformation** One could use a non-parametric estimator, such as decision trees or developments thereof, such as RandomForest, XGBoost, or HistGradientBoostingClassifier etc. thus obviating the need to transform the features to become Gaussian.\\n- **Make it a categorical variable** Rather than actually replacing the feature as a categorical variable, create a new additional feature as a categorical variable, perhaps with something like\\n\\n- `df['food_spending'] = np.where(df['FoodCourt'] > 1000, 'yes', 'no')`\\n\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] High cardinality &amp; High correlation](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309513) \\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\nThe author is sharing some findings of EDA:\\n\\n- `PassengerId` has a high cardinality: 8693 distinct values\\n- `Cabin` has a high cardinality: 6560 distinct values\\n- `Name` has a high cardinality: 8473 distinct values\\n- `FoodCourt` is highly correlated with VRDeck`\\n- `CryoSleep` is highly correlated with `Transported`\\n- `HomePlanet` is highly correlated with `Destination`\\n\\n[Tip - Don't forget about the Cabin! \\ud83d\\udcc8](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309693)\\nby [alexteboul](alexteboul)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"For a slight **increase in accuracy**, don't drop the `Cabin` column entirely from your modeling.\\\"\\n\\n**For Example**\\n```python\\n# split column and add new columns to df\\ntrain[['Deck', 'Num', 'Side']] = train['Cabin'].str.split('/', expand=True)\\n# display the dataframe\\ntrain.head()\\n```\\n- [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/alexteboul/space-titanic-eda-models-lb-0-799l)\\n\\n[How to Choose OneHotEncoding between LabelEncoding? I'll Answer!! (EDA Tip)](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309803) \\nby [kalelpark](kalelpark)\\n\\n- From the post:\\n\\n**We apply One-Hot Encoding when:**\\n\\n- The Categorical feature is not ordinal\\n- The number of categorical features is less so one-hot encoding can be effectively applied\\n\\n**We apply Label Encoding when:**\\n- The categorical feature is ordinal (like Primary school, high school)\\n- The number of categories is quite large as one-hot encoding can lead to high memory consumption\\n\\nThe author also shared a public [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/kalelpark/spaceship-titanic-solutions-for-beginner)\\n\\n[Might be a good way to fill some missing  value?](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310574) \\nby [gargantuar](gargantuar)\\n\\n- Found that for the passenger when the first part of the PassengerId is same ,the Homeplanet ,Cabin are also same.\\n- So, we can fill some missing value of these two values(about 50 in total 200),that might be able to improve the data quality.\\n\\n[Adding GENDER Feature based on NAME column](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309664) \\nby [sardorabdirayimov](sardorabdirayimov)\\n\\n- The notebook uses an [external web page](https://www.gpeters.com/names/baby-names.php) to identify gender based on the name\\n- Also: `Name` column in the dataset definitely helps to identify `gender`, `family`, `nationality` , `personality`\\n\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\udccc EDA\\ud83d\\udcc8 + FE\\ud83d\\udd25 + Comparison\\u2696\\ufe0f + Pseudo\\ud83c\\udfad](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309626) \\nby [hasanbasriakcay](hasanbasriakcay)\\n\\n- **Shared multiple notebooks:**\\n- [EDA](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-eda-fe-baseline)\\n- [Model Comparison](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pycaret-model-comparisons)\\n- [Pseudo Labeling](https://www.kaggle.com/hasanbasriakcay/spaceship-titanic-pseudo-labels-stacking)\\n\\n[Cabin Feature is more IMPORTANT than you believe](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/319152)\\nby [javigallego](javigallego)\\n\\n- Sharing a code snippet for splitting the Cabin feature into 3 new features.\\n```python\\ndef split_Cabin(df):\\n    df['Deck'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[0]\\n    df['Number'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[1]\\n    df['Side'] = df['Cabin'].str.split(\\\"/\\\", n=2, expand=True)[2]\\n    df.pop('Cabin')\\n    return df\\n```\\n\\n[Feature engineering results](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768)\\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n**Sharing the results of Feature Engineering:**\\n- drop VIP feature - 0.02% increase\\n- create an expenditure feature that sums the total money spent across the 5 amenities - 0.5% increase\\n- create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (RoomService, \\u2026,VRDeck) - 4.7% decrease\\n- create a cabin deck feature (A,B,\\u2026,T) - 0.35% increase\\n- create a cabin side feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase\\n- create a group size feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase\\n- create a no spending binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0 otherwise - 0.2% increase\\n- Create a solo feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase\\n- Create cabin region features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see here for details) - 0.2% increase-\\n- create a family size feature from last name - 0.0% change\\n- create binary age features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase\\n- same as above but drop the age column - 0.4% drop\\n\\n**Conclusions:**\\n- create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very helpful\\n- group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit\\n\\n[full notebook here](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide)\\n\\n[Cabin number chunking](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379) \\nby [samuelcortinhas](samuelcortinhas)\\n\\n- From the post: \\\"It seems that the cabin number is chunked into groups of 300 cabins, and within each group the target distribution is a little bit different.\\\"\\n![](https://i.postimg.cc/NjpRsTXT/Cabin-number-distribution.png)\\n\\n\\n[Speed up your kernel using Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314402) \\nby [lordozvlad](lordozvlad)\\n\\n-From the post: \\\"If you want to speed up your kernel you can use Intel\\u00ae Extension for Scikit-learn!\\\"\\n```python\\n!pip install scikit-learn-intelex\\n```\\n- [notebook:  Introduction to scikit-learn-intelex](https://www.kaggle.com/lordozvlad/introduction-to-scikit-learn-intelex/notebook)\\n\\n[\\ud83d\\ude80 Spaceship Titanic 0.79962 \\ud83d\\ude80](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312497) \\nby [rocklen](rocklen)\\n\\n- Sharing a [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/code/rocklen/spaceship-titanic-2-0-80079) with a score of 0.79962 using XGBoost + Randomized Search\\n\\n[Random Forest Perform significantly better in some cases than XGBoost](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/314044)\\nby [shivamnegi1993](shivamnegi1993)\\n\\n- Random Forest is performing better than XGBoost in some cases.\\n- Check cases on the original thread.\\n\\n[Some rules to fill NaNs](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/315987) \\nby [vdebout](vdebout)\\n\\n- The author shared some hardcoded rules to fill NaNs.\\n\\n- link between HomePlanet and CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on E, F,G\\n    Mars on D, E, F\\n    Europa on A, B, C, D, E, T\\n- persons in the same group all have the same CabinSide, possibly on different CabinDeck\\n    in groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are necessarily on CabinDeck:\\n    Earth on G\\n    Europa on B\\n    Mars on E or F\\n- for Europa groups with several CabinDeck, people with no bill are on deck B\\n- CabinNum are in increasing order of PassengerIdGroup for each (CabinDeck, CabinSide) => This is very useful but need a complex algorithm. All Cabins are occupied !\\n- People in a group have the same HomePlanet\\n- Surnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- Children have no bill\\n- CryoSleep have no bill\\n- People not Children and not CryoSleep with no bill all have Destination TRAPPIST-1e\\n- link between HomePlanet, VIP (also Age and CryoSleep):\\n    Earth no VIP\\n    Mars VIP have Age >= 18 and no CryoSleep and never goes to \\\"55 Cancri e\\\"\\n    Europa VIP have Age >= 25\\n    Europa with Age < 25 never goes to \\\"PSO J318.5-22\\\"\\n    Mars children are all transported\\n\\n**Approximative rules (with some exceptions):**\\n- Firstnames are found in a unique HomePlanet\\n- ToTal bill has minimum per HomePlanet and CabinDeck (Earth is around 300, Mars 400 and Europa 1000), be careful when filling with median\\n\\n\\n[Tip. Increase your score!](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/312173) \\nby [michael6141](michael6141)\\n\\n- Sharing a tip to increase your score: \\\"Try to average received probabilities on each validation split (list(probabilities)/len(probabilities)), predict_proba may help you. Averaging the model is a powerful tool to get a high validation score.\\\"\\n\\n[[Exploratory Data Analysis] Missing Values](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309514)\\nby [rishirajacharya](rishirajacharya)\\n\\n- Age has 179 (2.1%) missing values\\n- Destination has 182 (2.1%) missing values\\n- FoodCourt has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- HomePlanet has 201 (2.3%) missing values\\n- Spa has 183 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VIP has 203 (2.3%) missing values\\n- RoomService has 181 (2.1%) missing values\\n- VRDeck has 188 (2.2%) missing values\\n- Name has 200 (2.3%) missing values\\n- From the post:\\n- Cabin has 199 (2.3%) missing values\\n- ShoppingMall has 208 (2.4%) missing values\\n- CryoSleep has 217 (2.5%) missing values\\n\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/rishirajacharya/spaceship-titanic-detailed) about the missing values in the dataset.\\n\\n[[Spaceship Titanic] TensorFlow Extended - Towards ML Engineering ](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/328882)\\nby [usharengaraju](usharengaraju)\\n\\n- Sharing in depth analysis of the dataset using TensorFlow.\\n- Sharing a [public notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/harshjain123/time-series-arima-sarima) about the following time series concepts:\\n\\n\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/332081\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-06-20T09:06:34.291829800Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2022-06-22T15:28:53.153333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.023747Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 316379,\n    \"title\": \"Cabin number chunking\",\n    \"author\": \"Samuel Cortinhas\",\n    \"author_username\": \"samuelcortinhas\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"GRANDMASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 13,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"I've been analyzing the cabin feature today and I came across this insight. It seems that the cabin number is chunked into groups of 300 cabins, and within each group the target distribution is a little bit different.\\n\\n[![Cabin-number-distribution.png](https://i.postimg.cc/NjpRsTXT/Cabin-number-distribution.png)](https://postimg.cc/CRnRJRmL)\\n\\nThis means we can compress this information by creating a new feature that tracks which chunk the passenger is in. I implemented this in my notebook, you can see here for details. [https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide](https://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide)\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-04-01T15:40:25.267327100Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-15T11:38:51.183333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234588Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309513,\n    \"title\": \"[Exploratory Data Analysis] High cardinality & High correlation\",\n    \"author\": \"Rishiraj Acharya\",\n    \"author_username\": \"rishirajacharya\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 10,\n    \"comment_count\": 0,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"`PassengerId` has a high cardinality: **8693** distinct values\\n`Cabin` has a high cardinality: **6560** distinct values\\n`Name` has a high cardinality: **8473** distinct values\\n\\n`FoodCourt` is highly correlated with `VRDeck`\\n`CryoSleep` is highly correlated with `Transported`\\n`HomePlanet` is highly correlated with `Destination`\\n\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2001-44-11.png)\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2001-44-16.png)\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2001-44-20.png)\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2001-44-24.png)\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2001-44-28.png)\\n\\nMore detailed EDA can be found in [this notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/rishirajacharya/spaceship-titanic-detailed).\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309513\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-23T20:46:39.899645600Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-16T16:56:58.240Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.235323+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:20:09.234679Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 309514,\n    \"title\": \"[Exploratory Data Analysis] Missing Values\",\n    \"author\": \"Rishiraj Acharya\",\n    \"author_username\": \"rishirajacharya\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"MASTER\",\n    \"votes\": 8,\n    \"comment_count\": 7,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"`HomePlanet` has **201 (2.3%)** missing values\\n`CryoSleep` has **217 (2.5%)** missing values\\n`Cabin` has **199 (2.3%)** missing values\\n`Destination` has **182 (2.1%)** missing values\\n`Age` has **179 (2.1%)** missing values\\n`VIP` has **203 (2.3%)** missing values\\n`RoomService` has **181 (2.1%)** missing values\\n`FoodCourt` has **183 (2.1%)** missing values\\n`ShoppingMall` has **208 (2.4%)** missing values\\n`Spa` has **183 (2.1%)** missing values\\n`VRDeck` has **188 (2.2%)** missing values\\n`Name` has **200 (2.3%)** missing values\\n\\n![](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rishiraj/s3/main/spaceship-titanic/Screenshot%20from%202022-02-24%2002-24-40.png)\\n\\nMore detailed EDA can be found in [this notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/rishirajacharya/spaceship-titanic-detailed).\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309514\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-02-23T21:01:53.783227300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-16T16:59:27.286666700Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615981+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615175Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 310574,\n    \"title\": \"Might be a good way to fill some missing  value?\",\n    \"author\": \"Gargantuar\",\n    \"author_username\": \"gargantuar\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 8,\n    \"comment_count\": 11,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"I found that for the passenger when the first part of the PassengerId is same ,the Homeplanet ,Cabin are also same.So, I can fill some  missing value of these two values(about 50 in total 200),that might be able to improve the data quality.\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/310574\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2022-03-02T01:44:14.729994500Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2023-08-17T14:51:00.953333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615981+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615193Z\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"competition_id\": \"spaceship-titanic\",\n    \"discussion_id\": 576544,\n    \"title\": \"Data imputation making results worse?\",\n    \"author\": \"Sam Rohrer\",\n    \"author_username\": \"samrohrer\",\n    \"author_tier\": \"CONTRIBUTOR\",\n    \"votes\": 7,\n    \"comment_count\": 2,\n    \"body_markdown\": \"Hi everyone.  My team and I are trying this competition and we used CatBoost along with basic feature engineering to get a pretty good score, but we noticed that our score gets worse when we do data imputation instead of leaving NaN's.  Initially we filled NaN's with the mode of the column, then we added more sophisticated imputation by using patterns in the data (Everyone from deck A/B/C is from Europa, everyone from cabin G is from Earth, everyone under 13 or in cryosleep spends 0 dollars) but somehow this imputation makes our results worse consistently, and even the imputation by modes makes our results worse.  This is very hard for me to understand - since the NaN's in this competition really look like the creators just blanked out random cells, it's hard to imagine that any pattern of where the NaN's are has any bearing on anything, and when reading others discussing this competition they say their results improve with imputation.  Does anyone have any idea why this would happen?  This is our notebook:\\n\\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/samrohrer/spaceship-titanic-bad-imputation\",\n    \"url\": \"https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/576544\",\n    \"tags\": [],\n    \"created_at\": \"2025-05-05T16:48:48.348320300Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2025-05-16T10:06:40.293333300Z\",\n    \"last_fetched_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615981+00:00\",\n    \"ingested_at\": \"2026-06-13T00:10:32.615219Z\"\n  }\n]\n\n--- kernel signals ---\n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:31:   achieve the best performance using ensemble techniques.                      \n/tmp/arootd