{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"python ./scripts/discussion_read.py 316768 --competition-id spaceship-titanic > /tmp/disc_fe_results.txt\npython ./scripts/discussion_read.py 309693 --competition-id spaceship-titanic > /tmp/disc_cabin_tip.txt\npython ./scripts/discussion_read.py 316379 --competition-id spaceship-titanic > /tmp/disc_cabin_chunk.txt\nprintf '%s\\\\n' '--- Feature results ---'; sed -n '1,220p' /tmp/disc_fe_results.txt\nprintf '%s\\\\n' '--- Cabin tip ---'; sed -n '1,130p' /tmp/disc_cabin_tip.txt\nprintf '%s\\\\n' '--- Cabin chunk ---'; sed -n '1,160p' /tmp/disc_cabin_chunk.txt\nprintf '%s\\\\n' '--- model snippets ---'\nrg -n \\\"CatBoost|LGBM|XGB|RandomForest|ExtraTrees|GradientBoosting|VotingClassifier|Stacking|pycaret|compare_models|blend|tune_model|create_model|TFDF|RandomForestModel|accuracy|0\\\\.80|0\\\\.81|submission|predict_proba|threshold\\\" /tmp/gusthema_tfdf.txt /tmp/samuel_guide.txt /tmp/arunklenin_fe.txt /tmp/odins0n_models.txt /tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt | head -n 300\"","aggregated_output":"--- Feature results ---\nв•­в”Ђ Feature engineering results в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®\nв”‚ Author: Samuel Cortinhas | Votes: 55 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2022-04-03     в”‚\nв”‚ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316768      в”‚\nв•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї\n\nHere is a summary of the feature engineering I have tried so far and the results\nI got on the test set. The baseline I used can be found in my notebook here. All\nI did was add/drop 1 feature at a time and see how the final score changed.     \n\n вЂў drop VIP feature - 0.02% increase                                            \n вЂў create an expenditure feature that sums the total money spent across the 5   \n   amenities - 0.5% increase                                                    \n вЂў create expenditure feature and drop the 5 amenities (RoomService, ...,VRDeck)\n   - 4.7% decrease                                                              \n вЂў create a cabin deck feature (A,B,...,T) - 0.35% increase                     \n вЂў create a cabin side feature (P/S) - 0.9% increase                            \n вЂў create a group size feature from the PassengerId column - 0.1% increase      \n вЂў create a no spending binary feature that is 1 if no money was spent and 0    \n   otherwise - 0.2% increase                                                    \n вЂў Create a solo feature that tracks if passenger was travelling on their own   \n   (from PassengerId) - 0.2% increase                                           \n вЂў Create cabin region features according to chunks of 300 passengers (see here \n   for details) - 0.2% increase                                                 \n вЂў create a family size feature from last name - 0.0% change                    \n вЂў create binary age features for 0-18 yo, 18-25 yo, 25+ yo - 0.02% increase    \n вЂў same as above but drop the age column - 0.4% drop                            \n\nConclusions:                                                                    \n\n вЂў create total expenditure, cabin deck and cabin side features - these are very\n   helpful                                                                      \n вЂў group size, solo, no_spending and cabin regions also help a bit              \n\nDo you agree? What feature engineering have you tried and did it improve your   \nscore?                                                                          \n\nв”Ђв”Ђ 15 Comments в”Ђв”Ђ\n\nRohan Mudaliar в–І1 2022-04-19\npretty helpful                                                                  \n\nSatoshi_S 2022-04-21\nGreat post. I didn't come up with cabin region features on my own. I will give  \nit a try!!                                                                      \n\nChirag Desai 2022-04-28\nExcellent analysis.. I also played with features but didn't measure the impact. \nThis is good way of doing feature analysis. Taking one feature at a time and    \nchecking its impact on the score and then updating again. Did you do same with  \nNaN's? Please share if you have imputed values and checked the score, it will be\nvery helpful also. Thanks.                                                      \n\nFakhri Robi Aulia в–І7 2022-06-01\naccording to my analysis. The Spending could be divided into two parts. The     \nFirst one Service spending such as 'RoomService','Spa','VRDeck' and spending on \nshopping 'FoodCourt','ShoppingMall'. When I combined into all spending features \nthe correlation was -0.2. When separate into service_spending feature and       \nshopping_spending the correlation became -0.35 and 0.04 respectively.           \n\nMuhammad Irfan Azam 2022-06-02\nDropping VIP feature reduced my score to 4.6%                                   \n\nNoman Bukhari 2022-09-14\nHow do you know if your feature engineering might just be overfitting a model   \nrather than actually predicting better?                                         \n\ntka400 в–І1 2022-09-20\nData is devided by two parts - train and validation. If validation score much   \nless then the train score - it is overfitting                                   \n\nJayant Yadav 2022-12-29\nquite insightful!                                                               \n\nRoland Eriksson 2022-12-30\nFrom my analysis CryoSleep is the most important feature. The spending features \nseem important but confusing, I hesitate if I should create one single          \n\"billing/spending\" feature or split into expenditure groups. I have considered  \ncreating a \"solo\" feature, but from your results I doubt that will have any     \ngreat effect. Cabin side did not look useful to me, I may have to reconsider    \nthat.                                                                           \n\nabdelbasset Basto 2023-04-18\nperfect thanks alot                                                             \n\nIshan 2023-08-12\nThank you so much for this. I implement all this in my notebook. It's really    \nuseful.                                                                         \n\nBhunakit Chantaraseno 2023-09-21\nThanks. It's very useful.                                                       \n\nAndre Moreira 2023-10-16\nThank you for the analysis. I tried the idea of creating a total expenditure    \ncolumn and dropping the other ammenities, I can confirm that the model's        \nprediction gets worse.                                                          \n\nBased on a correlation analysis between the target variable (\"Y\") and the other \nvariables (\"X\"), I find interesting that with very few parameters (\"CryoSleep\", \n\"RoomService\", \"Spa\", \"VRDeck\") I get almost as good predicitons (Score: 0.7746)\nas with about all parameters included (0.78746).                                \n\nJacob Sultan 2024-07-08\nI've implemented an algorithm to fill most of the cabins correctly to eliminate \nthis need mostly for cabin chunking ! Please let me know what you think :)      \n\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/jacobsultan/how-to-impute-nearly-every-cabin-correct\nly/notebook                                                                     \n\nAyilhan 2025-06-10\nquite interesting                                                               \n\n--- Cabin tip ---\nв•­в”Ђ Tip - Don't forget about the Cabin! рџ“€ в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®\nв”‚ Author: Alex Teboul | Votes: 38 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2022-02-24          в”‚\nв”‚ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/309693      в”‚\nв•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї\n\nFor a slight increase in accuracy, don't drop the Cabin column entirely from    \nyour modeling.                                                                  \n\nFor example:                                                                    \n\n                                                                                \n # split column and add new columns to df                                       \n train[['Deck', 'Num', 'Side']] = train['Cabin'].str.split('/', expand=True)    \n # display the dataframe                                                        \n train.head()                                                                   \n                                                                                \n\nрџЊ† Screen-Shot-2022-02-24-at-4-07-00-PM.png                                     \n\n\n                                 Notebook Link                                  \n\nв”Ђв”Ђ 19 Comments в”Ђв”Ђ\n\nRobin S. 2022-02-25\nI will work on this feature next. Nice code :D                                  \n\nRaphael Filip 2022-02-26\nI'm trying to split the Cabin using R, but when I tried this:                   \n\nstrsplit(dados$Cabin, split = \"/\")                                              \n\nMy kaggle notebook was completely freezing. Does someone has any tip?           \n\nBill Cruise в–І5 2022-02-26\nSimilarly, PassengerId can be split into Group and Number for another slight    \ngain.                                                                           \n\n в–І4 2022-02-26\n\nRaphael Filip 2022-02-27\nThanks!!!!                                                                      \n\nWongi Park 2022-02-28\nGreat !!!рџ‘Ќ It's so useful!                                                     \n\nRandomRushGirl 2022-02-28\nYup, thinkin g of it logically (not from a code perspective) this makes a lot of\nsense so should see some correlation here. Thanks :)                            \n\nShivam Negi 2022-03-15\nGood find !  seems like there are some nice hidden features                     \n\nDigitalJester 2022-04-03\nMuch more elegant than what I did!                                              \n\n                                                                                \n data <- data %>%                                                               \n   mutate(Cab_len = nchar(Cabin)) %>%                                           \n   mutate(Deck.f = as.factor(str_sub(Cabin, 1, 1)),                             \n          CabinNum = as.integer(str_sub(Cabin, 3, (Cab_len - 2))),              \n          PorS.f = as.factor(str_sub(Cabin, Cab_len))) %>%                      \n   select(-\"Cab_len\")                                                           \n                                                                                \n\nAlexTheDataScientist 2022-04-11\nIs the increase in performance because this feature holds information or is it  \ncoincidental ? does this even matter if there is gain to be made ?              \n\nDigitalJester в–І4 2022-04-12\nThe size of group, ie the second part of PassengerId, is definitely helpful.    \nThis information is a little like the sibsp and parch variables in the original \nTitanic challenger.                                                             \n\nZub3r 2022-07-16\nYes !!! , you can get size of group with the help of that  and Weather that     \npassenger was travelling with Family or not                                     \n\nLuke DUTHOIT в–І1 2022-07-20\nI'm glad to discover that other people had the same idea, it means my intuition \nwasn't that bad ;) For the record, the deck position (after being label encoded \n: A-> 1, B-> 2, etc) and cabin number proved to be quite useful, but side (after\nbeing one hot encoded, and split into two features 'S' and 'P') not that much.  \nSee below : after hyper-parameters optimization/cross-validation on train set   \nwith an AdaBoostClassifier, I displayed features importance. The horizontal line\nis  equal to the inverse of the number of features, that is to say the          \ntheoretical importance if all features had the same importance for this         \nalgorithm. We see that features from Deck and Cabin are above, whereas features \nfrom Side are below...                                                          \n\nNoman Bukhari 2022-09-13\nI tried it with a SVM but my accuracy actually went down from about 78% to 76%, \nbut I'm sure it's because I didn't do it very well.                             \n\nZub3r 2022-09-15\nCan you please specify kernel trick used in training above SVM                  \n\nNoman Bukhari 2022-09-18\nIt was rbf, default sklearn value.                                              \n\nPeter Danilov 2023-05-27\nGreat idea! I had a feeling that with keeping it consolidated (not to mention   \ndropping), we'd lose valuable information.                                      \n\nOmikumar Bhavinkumar Makadia 2023-08-14\nThank you for the idea !!                                                       \n\nJacob Sultan 2024-07-08\nI've found an algorithm to impute most of the cabins without guessing! Please   \nlet me know what you think :)                                                   \n\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/jacobsultan/how-to-impute-nearly-every-cabin-correct\nly/notebook                                                                     \n\n--- Cabin chunk ---\nв•­в”Ђ Cabin number chunking в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®\nв”‚ Author: Samuel Cortinhas | Votes: 13 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2022-04-01     в”‚\nв”‚ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/spaceship-titanic/discussion/316379      в”‚\nв•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї\n\nI've been analyzing the cabin feature today and I came across this insight. It  \nseems that the cabin number is chunked into groups of 300 cabins, and within    \neach group the target distribution is a little bit different.                   \n\nрџЊ† Cabin-number-distribution.png                                                \n\nThis means we can compress this information by creating a new feature that      \ntracks which chunk the passenger is in. I implemented this in my notebook, you  \ncan see here for details.                                                       \nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/samuelcortinhas/spaceship-titanic-a-complete-guide  \n\nв”Ђв”Ђ 5 Comments в”Ђв”Ђ\n\nDigitalJester в–І3 2022-04-02\nNot all decks are equal! For example Deck T's highest cabin number is 4 while   \ndeck F has cabin numbers all the way upto 1894!                                 \n\nsamohao 2022-04-20\nWhat a nice comment!                                                            \n\nkikurage 2022-06-16\nGood analysis!!                                                                 \n\nJosh Miller 2022-07-11\nNoticed the same thing today. I like your approach for turning this into a      \nfeature!                                                                        \n\nOmikumar Bhavinkumar Makadia 2023-08-15\nNice Analysis !!                                                                \n\n--- model snippets ---\n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:1:Reading kernel: arootda/pycaret-visualization-optimization-0-81\n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:21:this library. I hope to study with people who are new to pycaret or who are     \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:22:curious about how to optimize through pycaret. I decided to focus on the        \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:30:   pycaret. We compared various optimization libraries and methods and tried to \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:33:Through this process, I got a score of 0.81. If you move this laptop as it is,  \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:34:you will get a score of 0.8097. Currently, the resulting hyperparameters are    \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:38:Information on the pycaret can be obtained from the following sites.            \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:39:https://pycaret.org/                                                            \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:54: !pip install pycaret                                                           \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:55: from pycaret.classification import *                                           \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:68: from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score                                     \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:150: submission = pd.read_csv(\"../input/spaceship-titanic/sample_submission.csv\")   \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:679:I used pycaret to proceed with the test method and optimization of models       \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:707: top4 = compare_models(n_select=4)                                              \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:731:learning in this model, you can get a score of about 0.8097.                    \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:735: catboost_best = create_model('catboost', nan_mode= 'Min',                      \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:750:                          subsample=0.800000011920929,                          \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:779: # catboost = tune_model(create_model('catboost'), choose_better = True, n_iter \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:785: # catboost2 = tune_model(create_model('catboost'), optimize='Accuracy',        \n/tmp/arootda_pycaret.txt:793: # catboost3 = tune_model(create_model('catboost'), 